00:18:53.810 --> 00:18:56.330
Since the third millennium B.C.

00:18:56.330 --> 00:19:03.090 position:56%
in Mesopotamia supernatural beings
were conceived as being combinations

00:19:03.090 --> 00:19:06.380
of human and animal
elements, and thus we see

00:19:06.380 --> 00:19:10.020 position:56%
in art human-headed bulls and lions,

00:19:10.020 --> 00:19:14.570
and statues of half
man-half bull or lion.

00:19:14.570 --> 00:19:19.660
During the 13th century B.C. the
Assyrians added another element

00:19:19.660 --> 00:19:25.850
to these monsters-- wings to
highlight their celestial nature.

00:19:25.850 --> 00:19:32.470 position:56%
Thus winged men and winged bulls and
lions began to appear in a variety

00:19:32.470 --> 00:19:38.860
of positions as you can see
in the [inaudible] here.

00:19:38.860 --> 00:19:43.120
Figures that quickly spread
out from Assyria to the rest

00:19:43.120 --> 00:19:45.340
of Mesopotamia and Upper Syria.

00:19:45.340 --> 00:19:51.180
As Assyria progressively became an
unmatched superpower at the dawn

00:19:51.180 --> 00:19:56.850
of the first millennium B.C.
Assyrians stoned the monsters

00:19:56.850 --> 00:20:02.890
into [inaudible] placed
almost always at gateways.

00:20:02.890 --> 00:20:07.100
Here they play two roles--
architectural and religious.

00:20:07.100 --> 00:20:15.330
In architecture the [inaudible]
are mere jumps upon which arches

00:20:15.330 --> 00:20:17.410
of gates and doorways rest.

00:20:17.410 --> 00:20:22.740
And in religion they are protective
deities not much different

00:20:22.740 --> 00:20:27.150
from the Judeo-Christian
concept of angels.

00:20:27.150 --> 00:20:30.370
There are three main
types of [inaudible]--

00:20:30.370 --> 00:20:37.690
the Centaur, made of the upper body
of man and the lower body of lion,

00:20:37.690 --> 00:20:43.430
attested monumentally only
during the ninth century B.C.,

00:20:43.430 --> 00:20:53.150 position:56%
the Anthropomorphic Winged bull,
and the Anthropomorphic Winged Lion.

00:20:53.150 --> 00:20:58.020
The latter two are known from the
ninth to the seventh centuries.

00:20:58.020 --> 00:21:01.530
The Assyrians portrayed
these monsters

00:21:01.530 --> 00:21:07.710
with the stylistic features known
to the Assyrians of that period.

00:21:07.710 --> 00:21:15.300
They all wear cylindrical tiaras
with horns seen in other deities,

00:21:15.300 --> 00:21:17.890
but the earrings hanging
from the ears of some

00:21:17.890 --> 00:21:23.010
of the [inaudible] are also worn
by Assyrian kings and dignitaries.

00:21:23.010 --> 00:21:26.530
Some were found in
archaeological digs, in fact.

00:21:26.530 --> 00:21:30.980
The hair which covers the cheeks,
the chin and part of the chest,

00:21:30.980 --> 00:21:36.090
and which also falls at the back
of the head, is always plated just

00:21:36.090 --> 00:21:40.920
as the hair of contemporary
kings and people is.

00:21:40.920 --> 00:21:42.740
And the depiction of [inaudible]

00:21:42.740 --> 00:21:47.040
and people the eyebrows
are thick and continuous.

00:21:47.040 --> 00:21:51.380
The eyes are bulgy and the
nose is slightly round,

00:21:51.380 --> 00:21:54.890
anatomical features known to
Mediterranean people in general.

00:21:54.890 --> 00:22:01.930
One of the most remarkable Assyrian
achievements in art is to express

00:22:01.930 --> 00:22:06.270
in the same work different
positions at the same time.

00:22:06.270 --> 00:22:12.880
Some of the [inaudible] are
depicted with five legs to be seen

00:22:12.880 --> 00:22:17.850
in a profile in a walking
position as if patrolling,

00:22:17.850 --> 00:22:23.430
and in front in a resting
position of guards at entrances.

00:22:23.430 --> 00:22:28.380
These peculiar anatomical features
dates to the ninth century B.C.,

00:22:28.380 --> 00:22:32.890
but Assyrians expressed
already during the 13th century

00:22:32.890 --> 00:22:38.720
in a relief showing
King Tukulti-Ninurta I

00:22:38.720 --> 00:22:42.710
in two worshipping attitudes--
standing and kneeling.

00:22:42.710 --> 00:22:47.580
The fact that the Assyrian artist
at the time of Ashurbanipal,

00:22:47.580 --> 00:22:52.030
seventh century B.C., also
depicted a hunting lion

00:22:52.030 --> 00:22:58.180
in three positions coming out of
the cage, moving towards the king

00:22:58.180 --> 00:23:04.120
and jumping at him highlights
a centuries-old practice among

00:23:04.120 --> 00:23:05.450
the Assyrians.

00:23:05.450 --> 00:23:07.000
The [inaudible] are mentioned

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:09.920
in Assyrian royal inscriptions
naming them

00:23:09.920 --> 00:23:14.140
and defining their
functions within the palace.

00:23:14.140 --> 00:23:17.930
The two frequent names
are the Lamashtu,

00:23:17.930 --> 00:23:22.950
she's a female, or
Lamashtu and Shadu.

00:23:22.950 --> 00:23:29.030
The Lamashtu may have its origin
in the Sumerian protective goddess,

00:23:29.030 --> 00:23:33.750
Lama, and is always a good
genius, a good spirit.

00:23:33.750 --> 00:23:36.520
By contrast the name Shadu refers

00:23:36.520 --> 00:23:40.890
to two different spirits--
one good and one bad.

00:23:40.890 --> 00:23:43.790
But when Shadu accompanies the name

00:23:43.790 --> 00:23:48.130
of Lamashtu Shadu is
always the good spirit.

00:23:48.130 --> 00:23:51.440
Modern Assyrians know
the name Shada,

00:23:51.440 --> 00:23:58.590 position:56%
devil from which the word Shaitan,
devilish or foolish person, derives.

00:23:58.590 --> 00:24:05.100
I will expand now to talk a
little bit about laurel leafs.

00:24:05.100 --> 00:24:07.340
The Assyrian artists also worked

00:24:07.340 --> 00:24:11.080
with the stone slabs
recording religious, military

00:24:11.080 --> 00:24:14.370
and hunting scenes
carved in laurel leafs.

00:24:14.370 --> 00:24:17.830
Since ancient Mesopotamian
buildings were constructed

00:24:17.830 --> 00:24:20.840
with mud bricks stone
slabs were placed

00:24:20.840 --> 00:24:24.290
against their lower
walls in protection.

00:24:24.290 --> 00:24:30.010
The local limestone was
readily available in Assyria,

00:24:30.010 --> 00:24:34.210
and with it until recently
churches, synagogues, mosques

00:24:34.210 --> 00:24:36.250
and houses were constructed.

00:24:36.250 --> 00:24:42.140
The practice of depicting
sceneries on such slabs is known

00:24:42.140 --> 00:24:46.330
in Mesopotamia and Syria, but
the maturity of the Assyrian art,

00:24:46.330 --> 00:24:51.760 position:56%
even in the ninth century, indicates
an indigenous practice dated much

00:24:51.760 --> 00:24:55.100
earlier than that century.

00:24:55.100 --> 00:24:57.810
The first depicted
slabs date to the time

00:24:57.810 --> 00:25:01.870
of the ninth century Ashurbanipal I

00:25:01.870 --> 00:25:07.440
in his capital city Kalhu
nowadays called Nimrud.

00:25:07.440 --> 00:25:10.500
The scenery is essentially
religious and even

00:25:10.500 --> 00:25:16.790
when it includes hunting episodes.

00:25:16.790 --> 00:25:20.830
It shows the king with a variety

00:25:20.830 --> 00:25:24.900
of winged genies including
eagle-headed men

00:25:24.900 --> 00:25:32.740
and winged men standing or kneeling
on both sides of a stylized tree.

00:25:32.740 --> 00:25:39.720
The genies hold bales and cords
while the king carries a libation

00:25:39.720 --> 00:25:44.490
bowl in the right hand and holds
a staff with the left hand.

00:25:44.490 --> 00:25:49.580
In another [inaudible] scene the
king is seen seated with a bowl

00:25:49.580 --> 00:25:57.850
in his hand and surrounded
by attendants and genies.

00:25:57.850 --> 00:26:01.030
Military and hunting scenes
dominated art of the eighth

00:26:01.030 --> 00:26:03.550
and seventh centuries B.C. in line

00:26:03.550 --> 00:26:05.750
with the territorial
expansion of Assyria.

00:26:05.750 --> 00:26:11.980
In both cases the king is the
focus of the scenes with no place

00:26:11.980 --> 00:26:18.590
for genies or other divinities
including the national guard Ashur.

00:26:18.590 --> 00:26:23.470
We see the king participating in
warfare and hunting wild animals,

00:26:23.470 --> 00:26:27.080
namely lions, and in
both cases he is depicted

00:26:27.080 --> 00:26:32.990
as a human being proving
his prowess in hunting.

00:26:32.990 --> 00:26:37.560
Military scenes include sieges,
deportations and impaling,

00:26:37.560 --> 00:26:41.300
violent tactics used
by all ancient nations.

00:26:41.300 --> 00:26:48.070
Even is these brutal contexts the
Assyrian artist added environmental

00:26:48.070 --> 00:26:54.870
sceneries including rivers
filled with fish and crabs,

00:26:54.870 --> 00:27:00.330
mountains covered with
trees and shrubs,

00:27:00.330 --> 00:27:04.560
and all kinds of birds
flying in the open skies.

00:27:04.560 --> 00:27:11.850
Lines of soldiers and prisoners
of war are traced symmetrically

00:27:11.850 --> 00:27:15.430
and harmoniously with
lines of trees.

00:27:15.430 --> 00:27:21.400
And since this arrangement recurs
nearly in all military scenes it is

00:27:21.400 --> 00:27:27.190
as if the artist involved nature
in otherwise bloody events.

00:27:27.190 --> 00:27:32.670
In the siege of Lachish,
a biblical city in Israel,

00:27:32.670 --> 00:27:34.630
which the late century
Sennacherib [inaudible],

00:27:34.630 --> 00:27:39.120
the artist produced a
well-conceived composition.

00:27:39.120 --> 00:27:42.310
The scene begins at the bottom

00:27:42.310 --> 00:27:46.680
with the drafted armies marching
toward the city of Lachish located

00:27:46.680 --> 00:27:51.430
in the middle of the way, and then
progresses toward the seated king

00:27:51.430 --> 00:27:54.680
who occupies the top
of the composition.

00:27:54.680 --> 00:28:00.270
The military scenes include a
variety of weapons, siege engines,

00:28:00.270 --> 00:28:04.970
defensive tactics and
different throngs of soldiers.

00:28:10.040 --> 00:28:15.290
The artist also traced the
topography of foreign countries.

00:28:15.290 --> 00:28:18.890
For example, here we have boats,
whether they are maritime,

00:28:18.890 --> 00:28:23.710
mountainous or just plain lands,
foreign people are depicted

00:28:23.710 --> 00:28:27.010
by the way they physically
looked and dressed up

00:28:27.010 --> 00:28:30.620
and the type of works
they undertook.

00:28:30.620 --> 00:28:35.590
Besides military events peace
treaties are fittingly recorded.

00:28:35.590 --> 00:28:42.650
And the scene shown in the throne
of King [inaudible] III the treaty

00:28:42.650 --> 00:28:45.480
between warring kings is concluded

00:28:45.480 --> 00:28:51.440
by probably the first
political handshaking.

00:28:51.440 --> 00:28:57.260
A rare scene even in antiquity and
you can see them shaking the hands.

00:28:57.260 --> 00:29:00.420
Hunting depictions are
particularly interesting

00:29:00.420 --> 00:29:05.800
because they show striking realism
never detected in ancient art.

00:29:05.800 --> 00:29:11.530
Hunted lions are shown
suffering, reeling and agonizing,

00:29:11.530 --> 00:29:19.110
but one lioness, defiant
even while succumbing

00:29:19.110 --> 00:29:21.630
to arrows penetrating her body.

00:29:21.630 --> 00:29:25.590
No artist in antiquity had every
reached the artistic standard

00:29:25.590 --> 00:29:30.750
that the Assyrians had so
brilliantly achieved in art.

00:29:30.750 --> 00:29:37.300
Artists also portrayed people
hunting wild animals and bulls

00:29:37.300 --> 00:29:41.340
as a scene in some
delightful scenes.

00:29:41.340 --> 00:29:45.790
The military and hunting activities
were also painted on walls

00:29:45.790 --> 00:29:49.530
with vivid colors and
gracious lines.

00:29:49.530 --> 00:29:55.280
They survive in a few Assyrian
provincial cities of Syria.

00:29:55.280 --> 00:29:59.170
The paintings reflect the ability
of the Assyrian artists to work

00:29:59.170 --> 00:30:06.280
with pigments and drawings
creating charming sceneries.

00:30:06.280 --> 00:30:09.750
Ivory works-- a great number of
ivory objects were [inaudible]

00:30:09.750 --> 00:30:14.730
in Assyria especially in
the capital Kalhu, Nimrud.

00:30:14.730 --> 00:30:17.890
While the art of these
objects betrays Egyptian

00:30:17.890 --> 00:30:25.040
and Syrian influences some objects
exhibit Mesopotamian motives.

00:30:25.040 --> 00:30:27.730
Since the Assyrians were brilliant

00:30:27.730 --> 00:30:32.370
in art some ivory works
must have been produced

00:30:32.370 --> 00:30:35.180
by Assyrian craftsman in Assyria.

00:30:35.180 --> 00:30:39.260
One can admire what I call
the Assyrian Mona Lisa

00:30:39.260 --> 00:30:45.820
with her subtle smile the
[inaudible] looking lady

00:30:45.820 --> 00:30:54.240
at the window, and the truly
delightful cow suckling her calf

00:30:54.240 --> 00:30:58.510
while turning her head towards
the latter in affection.

00:30:58.510 --> 00:31:04.650
Even if these works may not
be Assyrian they tell much

00:31:04.650 --> 00:31:09.940 position:56%
about the finesse and charm of their
owners since the Assyrian used them

00:31:09.940 --> 00:31:12.480
to ornate their chairs,
beds, thrones

00:31:12.480 --> 00:31:15.810
and other pieces of furniture.

00:31:16.850 --> 00:31:24.810
Lastly, jewelry work-- in producing
jewelry the Assyrians reached

00:31:24.810 --> 00:31:27.020
such a professional standard

00:31:27.020 --> 00:31:32.080
that not even our modern
machines can reach.

00:31:32.080 --> 00:31:33.980
And I'm not exaggerating.

00:31:33.980 --> 00:31:40.270
A cache of jewels was uncovered in
Nimrud in 1989 in a royal grave,

00:31:40.270 --> 00:31:45.530
and it is so stunning that the King
Tut's treasures looks quite pale

00:31:45.530 --> 00:31:48.010
in comparison with it.

00:31:48.010 --> 00:31:51.680
The treasure of Nimrud
includes pairs of earrings

00:31:51.680 --> 00:31:55.680
with hanging bells,
pomegranate-shaped pendants,

00:31:55.680 --> 00:32:02.600 position:56%
solid gold bracelets, pairs of cuffs
made of heavy gold, bangles, anklets

00:32:02.600 --> 00:32:08.630
and the truly unique
and splendid headbands.

00:32:08.630 --> 00:32:15.760
The headband is made of fine-woven
herringbone-patterned gold strands,

00:32:15.760 --> 00:32:21.260
and consists of six gold
ribbons connected by hinges

00:32:21.260 --> 00:32:26.720
with five discs each inlaid
around a precious stone,

00:32:26.720 --> 00:32:32.860
and a rectangular plaque decorated
with rosettes around its edges.

00:32:32.860 --> 00:32:37.460
The plaque is inlaid with
two square precious stones

00:32:37.460 --> 00:32:43.330
and with tassels attached
to its lower edge.

00:32:43.330 --> 00:32:49.560
The gold necklace is made
of a tube [inaudible]

00:32:49.560 --> 00:32:54.370
with alternating vertical
and horizontal wavy lines.

00:32:54.370 --> 00:32:59.880
Twenty-eight almond-shaped pendants
are suspended around the tube

00:32:59.880 --> 00:33:03.640
by a gold wire passing
through rings.

00:33:03.640 --> 00:33:08.440
Its clasp is made of two
entwined dragon's heads

00:33:08.440 --> 00:33:13.670
and Mesopotamian motif that
continue to be seen in the art

00:33:13.670 --> 00:33:17.850
of medieval churches
in the north of Iraq.

00:33:17.850 --> 00:33:22.050
One would add four gold bowls.

00:33:22.050 --> 00:33:26.380
Two of which inscribed with
names of Assyrian queens.

00:33:26.380 --> 00:33:32.560
In producing these gold vessels the
Assyrian goldsmith imitated bowls

00:33:32.560 --> 00:33:35.780
made of exceptionally thin walls,

00:33:35.780 --> 00:33:39.180
called by archaeologists
palace ware,

00:33:39.180 --> 00:33:42.000
that is abundantly found in Nimrud.

00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:48.680
In conclusion, Assyrian artists
added elegance to an empire known

00:33:48.680 --> 00:33:52.790
for its military prowess and
its administrative regal.

00:33:52.790 --> 00:33:54.590
Thank you.

