00:36:40.460 --> 00:36:44.470
But first what is the
Epic of Gilgamesh about?

00:36:44.470 --> 00:36:47.500
Well, it's human mortality
and the fear

00:36:47.500 --> 00:36:49.740
of death are the principle themes.

00:36:49.740 --> 00:36:55.100
The death of Gilgamesh's
companion, Enkidu, after a series

00:36:55.100 --> 00:36:58.980
of shared adventures
sets Gilgamesh on a quest

00:36:58.980 --> 00:37:02.760
to meet the immortal survivor
of the flood, Utnapishtim,

00:37:02.760 --> 00:37:07.590
the Mesopotamian Noah, to learn
the secret of immortality.

00:37:07.590 --> 00:37:11.520
It's a quest, of course, in
which he ultimately fails,

00:37:11.520 --> 00:37:16.130
but acquires a great deal
of wisdom in the process.

00:37:16.130 --> 00:37:19.710
So, the epic is about the
acquisition of self-knowledge,

00:37:19.710 --> 00:37:23.660
as well as the divinely-ordained
scheme of things,

00:37:23.660 --> 00:37:26.230
a wisdom that the gods
gave to humans

00:37:26.230 --> 00:37:31.930
in the antediluvian age before the
flood, but was lost with the flood.

00:37:31.930 --> 00:37:37.170
We of course celebrate Gilgamesh
as the first masterpiece

00:37:37.170 --> 00:37:39.230
of world literature
and, certainly today,

00:37:39.230 --> 00:37:42.770
it's the best known
Mesopotamian composition.

00:37:42.770 --> 00:37:44.450
But what we often overlook is

00:37:44.450 --> 00:37:50.090
that Gilgamesh also had a
substantial following in antiquity,

00:37:50.090 --> 00:37:53.320
to judge by its wide
circulation and longevity

00:37:53.320 --> 00:37:56.860
and artistic representation,
it enjoyed popularity

00:37:56.860 --> 00:37:58.950
in the ancient world as well.

00:37:58.950 --> 00:38:03.660
The major themes of the epic
resonate with us just as much

00:38:03.660 --> 00:38:05.780
as they did with the ancients.

00:38:05.780 --> 00:38:11.250
And this is what gives the epic
its universal and timeless appeal.

00:38:11.250 --> 00:38:18.400 position:56%
And here you have an example of a
first millennium B.C. cylinder seal.

00:38:18.400 --> 00:38:24.080
It depicts Gilgamesh and Enkidu
dispatching the Bull of Heaven

00:38:24.080 --> 00:38:28.730
as its recounted in
tablet six of the epic.

00:38:28.730 --> 00:38:33.630
Here is a relief of a
hero, it's not definite,

00:38:33.630 --> 00:38:37.290
but many people have
wanted to identify

00:38:37.290 --> 00:38:39.760
with Gilgamesh overpowering a lion.

00:38:39.760 --> 00:38:42.800
This is from the throne
room of Sargon II.

00:38:42.800 --> 00:38:46.680
And at the very least it recalls
a passage from the beginning

00:38:46.680 --> 00:38:51.780 position:56%
of tablet nine of the Epic of
Gilgamesh where Gilgamesh distraught

00:38:51.780 --> 00:38:56.740 position:56%
after the death of Enkidu reverts to
this primitive state becoming a sort

00:38:56.740 --> 00:39:04.410
of child of nature before beginning
his quest to seek out Utnapishtim.

00:39:04.410 --> 00:39:09.450
In the epic, of course,
we have Humbaba,

00:39:09.450 --> 00:39:12.000
who's the protector
of the Cedar Forest.

00:39:12.000 --> 00:39:14.500
He's decapitated by Enkidu.

00:39:14.500 --> 00:39:18.410
And we have a great variety
of mask-like representations

00:39:18.410 --> 00:39:21.890
from Mesopotamian depicting the
head of Humbaba that were used

00:39:21.890 --> 00:39:25.480
as probably protective amulets,
and these have also survived

00:39:25.480 --> 00:39:28.360
in the archaeological record.

00:39:28.360 --> 00:39:30.310
Well, images from the epic,

00:39:30.310 --> 00:39:33.470
particularly those involving
Humbaba, these were very ,

00:39:33.470 --> 00:39:37.090
very popular, they liked this part
of the story a lot, and is slang

00:39:37.090 --> 00:39:41.210
or found really far and wide in
Mesopotamia, again a testament

00:39:41.210 --> 00:39:43.980
to the epic in antiquity
and its popularity.

00:39:43.980 --> 00:39:47.110
We have here this piece from
the Old Babylonian Period,

00:39:47.110 --> 00:39:51.090
from the second millennium
B.C., another piece all the way

00:39:51.090 --> 00:39:58.470
up from the Anatolian capital in
Turkey, and even in Southeast Iran.

00:39:58.470 --> 00:40:02.970
Now, Gilgamesh is at
present a damaged

00:40:02.970 --> 00:40:06.580
and only partially
complete masterpiece.

00:40:06.580 --> 00:40:11.250
What you see here are some of the
largest fragments of the epic.

00:40:11.250 --> 00:40:15.700
As many of you no doubt know it's
written in the cuneiform script

00:40:15.700 --> 00:40:18.140
and it represents standard
Babylonian.

00:40:18.140 --> 00:40:20.070
That's the canonical version of it.

00:40:20.070 --> 00:40:23.090
This is a dialect of
Akkadian, a Semitic language.

00:40:23.090 --> 00:40:28.660 position:56%
And these bits and pieces have to be
assembled in a jigsaw-like puzzle.

00:40:28.660 --> 00:40:32.240
Unfortunately, only
2,000 of the 3,000 lines

00:40:32.240 --> 00:40:33.950
of the epic are preserved,

00:40:33.950 --> 00:40:38.690
but because Mesopotamian literary
texts were copied and recopied

00:40:38.690 --> 00:40:41.520
as scribal exercises
there's hope that more,

00:40:41.520 --> 00:40:48.120
and perhaps eventually the entire
epic, may one day be recovered.

00:40:48.120 --> 00:40:51.880
Now, when we speak of the history
of Gilgamesh it's really a story

00:40:51.880 --> 00:40:57.570
that centers around three
Mesopotamian cities-- Uruk, Ur--

00:40:57.570 --> 00:41:01.270
not to be confused with
Uruk-- and Nineveh.

00:41:01.270 --> 00:41:05.120
Now, Gilgamesh hailed from
the city state of Uruk.

00:41:05.120 --> 00:41:07.170
He was the King of Uruk.

00:41:07.170 --> 00:41:09.590
And Uruk is a very special place.

00:41:09.590 --> 00:41:15.160
It emerges at the end of the fourth
millennium B.C., or 34, 3,500,

00:41:15.160 --> 00:41:18.940
as the world's first
city, first metropolis.

00:41:18.940 --> 00:41:23.230
And it's the place where writing is
first invented in all likelihood.

00:41:23.230 --> 00:41:27.340 position:56%
Now, Gilgamesh didn't rule at that
point in time, but he ruled probably

00:41:27.340 --> 00:41:33.490
about five, six, 700 years
later, around 27, 2,800 B.C. So,

00:41:33.490 --> 00:41:37.230
about easily 500 years after
the invention of writing, but,

00:41:37.230 --> 00:41:41.610
unfortunately, just before or
just on the cusp of history

00:41:41.610 --> 00:41:44.170
when we had the first
historical texts.

00:41:44.170 --> 00:41:46.950
So, often people ask was
Gilgamesh a real person.

00:41:46.950 --> 00:41:49.880
Well, we don't know for sure
because we have no texts

00:41:49.880 --> 00:41:54.000
that we can relate directly to him,
but they're good reasons to assume

00:41:54.000 --> 00:41:58.580
that there is a real person
behind the actual legend.

00:41:58.580 --> 00:42:04.230
Now, Ur, on the other hand, was the
seat of a very important dynasty

00:42:04.230 --> 00:42:05.930
at the end of the third millennium.

00:42:05.930 --> 00:42:08.350
So, now we're fast
forwarding again another five,

00:42:08.350 --> 00:42:12.510
600 years down to 2100 B.C.,
and this dynasty was known

00:42:12.510 --> 00:42:16.560
as the third dynasty of
Ur or the Ur III Period.

00:42:16.560 --> 00:42:20.290
Now, the kings of Ur claimed
a very special bond with Urok.

00:42:20.290 --> 00:42:23.280
And they commissioned several
stories about Gilgamesh

00:42:23.280 --> 00:42:26.280
in the Sumerian language,
which is completely unrelated

00:42:26.280 --> 00:42:29.310
to standard Babylonian.

00:42:29.310 --> 00:42:34.180
Nineveh, in this story, now we fast
forward again another 1,500 years,

00:42:34.180 --> 00:42:39.450
was as we heard the capital of the
vast Assyrian empire Ashurbanipal,

00:42:39.450 --> 00:42:44.590 position:56%
we just heard much about, was one
of the greatest Mesopotamian rulers.

00:42:44.590 --> 00:42:48.220
He ruled his empire from Nineveh
in the seventh century B.C.,

00:42:48.220 --> 00:42:51.370
and he's famous for his
military exploits, of course,

00:42:51.370 --> 00:42:54.450
but he was also something
of a renaissance man,

00:42:54.450 --> 00:42:58.450
and one of the few Mesopotamian
monarchs to claim literacy.

00:42:58.450 --> 00:43:01.770
At his capital Nineveh
he established one

00:43:01.770 --> 00:43:06.840 position:56%
of the great libraries of antiquity,
the Library of Ashurbanipal.

00:43:06.840 --> 00:43:10.550
And it's from this library that
we have the best preserved copies

00:43:10.550 --> 00:43:13.150
of the Epic of Gilgamesh.

00:43:13.150 --> 00:43:20.290 position:56%
So, our story begins at Ur around
2100 B.C. during this Ur III Period.

00:43:20.290 --> 00:43:24.280
Now, as I'd mentioned, the rulers
of Ur claimed a special bond

00:43:24.280 --> 00:43:27.760
with the early Urok rulers,
particularly with Gilgamesh,

00:43:27.760 --> 00:43:31.580
even though these rulers
of Urok preceded them

00:43:31.580 --> 00:43:34.670
by a good five, 600 years.

00:43:34.670 --> 00:43:38.940
But at Ur they saw Urok at
the time of Gilgamesh as sort

00:43:38.940 --> 00:43:43.580 position:56%
of a heroic Sumerian golden age,
and they saw themselves as the heirs

00:43:43.580 --> 00:43:47.060
and stewards of this
ancient tradition.

00:43:47.060 --> 00:43:50.930
The Ur III kings sought to
legitimize their own rule

00:43:50.930 --> 00:43:57.710
by constantly connecting themselves
with Urok and its bygone rulers,

00:43:57.710 --> 00:44:00.340
and with Gilgamesh in particular.

00:44:00.340 --> 00:44:07.050
The dynasty's greatest
ruler was Shulgi,

00:44:07.050 --> 00:44:10.830
who consolidated the
incipient empire

00:44:10.830 --> 00:44:12.800
that he inherited from his father.

00:44:12.800 --> 00:44:18.270
Shulgi, who frequently referred
to himself as Brother Friend

00:44:18.270 --> 00:44:23.090
of Gilgamesh, was like Ashurbanipal
some 1,500 years later, literate

00:44:23.090 --> 00:44:27.350
and had a special penchant
for learning.

00:44:28.450 --> 00:44:33.300
So, it comes as no surprise
that given the spirit

00:44:33.300 --> 00:44:39.300
of the Ur III Period generally, and
Shulgi's inclinations for education

00:44:39.300 --> 00:44:42.450
in particular, that it was
during this period that a cycle

00:44:42.450 --> 00:44:44.940
of poems celebrating Gilgamesh

00:44:44.940 --> 00:44:49.390
and his exploits was first
committed to writing.

00:44:49.390 --> 00:44:53.910
And no doubt these stories drew
upon longstanding oral traditions

00:44:53.910 --> 00:44:57.150
that must have been in
circulation since the days

00:44:57.150 --> 00:44:59.280
of the first dynasty of Urok.

00:44:59.280 --> 00:45:05.400
So, there are actually five
primary Sumerian Gilgamesh stories.

00:45:05.400 --> 00:45:09.960
Now, likely these poems were
composed to be performed

00:45:09.960 --> 00:45:12.600
at court before Shulgi and others.

00:45:12.600 --> 00:45:14.620
And perhaps they were set to music.

00:45:14.620 --> 00:45:18.600
But these stories have a very
laconic abrupt style suggesting

00:45:18.600 --> 00:45:21.100
that they were probably
abbreviations

00:45:21.100 --> 00:45:23.690
of traditional oral compositions.

00:45:23.690 --> 00:45:27.490
One possible purpose for writing
down of these poems may have been

00:45:27.490 --> 00:45:29.320
for training singers

00:45:29.320 --> 00:45:33.520
and for preserving the
outline of an oral performance.

00:45:33.520 --> 00:45:37.920
So, what was the historical
development of Gilgamesh?

00:45:37.920 --> 00:45:39.970
Well, it needs to be pointed

00:45:39.970 --> 00:45:45.020 position:56%
out that these Sumerian stories they
share a broad theme of Gilgamesh,

00:45:45.020 --> 00:45:47.420
but they're largely
disconnected from one another.

00:45:47.420 --> 00:45:52.590
There's no such thing as
a Sumerian Gilgamesh Epic.

00:45:52.590 --> 00:45:56.510
It was only in the
Old Babylonian Period

00:45:56.510 --> 00:45:59.150
with the first Akkadian
version of Gilgamesh

00:45:59.150 --> 00:46:02.630
that we have the first
true Epic of Gilgamesh.

00:46:02.630 --> 00:46:05.930
And this is the Old Babylonian
version of the Epic of Gilgamesh.

00:46:05.930 --> 00:46:09.220
And what this represents
it pulled together all

00:46:09.220 --> 00:46:12.460
of these Sumerian sources, it
added a lot more that wasn't

00:46:12.460 --> 00:46:16.520
in the original Sumerian stories,
had no counterpart in them,

00:46:16.520 --> 00:46:19.770
and it brought it together
into sort of a coherent whole.

00:46:19.770 --> 00:46:23.570
Now, the Old Babylonian version
of Gilgamesh is far from complete,

00:46:23.570 --> 00:46:26.880
but it's a poem of
tremendous beauty and power.

00:46:26.880 --> 00:46:31.110
And the opening line of this
story, and it's served as the title

00:46:31.110 --> 00:46:34.360
for compositions in antiquity,
the first line was the title,

00:46:34.360 --> 00:46:39.160
is translated as the one
who is greatest among kings.

00:46:39.160 --> 00:46:43.420
And this is really a very apt title
because the poem is really a hymn

00:46:43.420 --> 00:46:47.080
to heroism in knightly might.

00:46:47.080 --> 00:46:50.190
Now, in the Middle
Babylonian Period,

00:46:50.190 --> 00:46:53.490
so that we're fast forwarding
now to the second half

00:46:53.490 --> 00:46:57.900
of the second millennium,
so, 1600 to 1000 B.C.,

00:46:57.900 --> 00:47:01.540
Gilgamesh spreads throughout
the ancient Near East

00:47:01.540 --> 00:47:05.510
as Akkadian becomes the lingua
franca of the Near East,

00:47:05.510 --> 00:47:09.070 position:56%
it spreads to Northern
Mesopotamia, it spreads to Anatolia,

00:47:09.070 --> 00:47:13.270
and it takes on various
versions and translations.

00:47:13.270 --> 00:47:19.100
What happens then around 1300
to 1000 is very important,

00:47:19.100 --> 00:47:22.940
because then what we have now is
the canonization of Gilgamesh.

00:47:22.940 --> 00:47:25.310
We have all of these
disparate versions.

00:47:25.310 --> 00:47:29.360
And then at the end of the second
millennium the story is eventually

00:47:29.360 --> 00:47:32.520
canonized, and it's written
in the literary dialect,

00:47:32.520 --> 00:47:35.440
standard Babylonian that
was actually never spoken.

00:47:35.440 --> 00:47:38.080
And when you go and you
buy the Epic of Gilgamesh

00:47:38.080 --> 00:47:41.760
at a bookstore what you're
reading is this canonical version

00:47:41.760 --> 00:47:46.970
that was written at this period.

00:47:46.970 --> 00:47:50.250
Now, this story, the canonical
version of the Epic of Gilgamesh,

00:47:50.250 --> 00:47:54.790
is attributed by ancient sources
to a scribe, an [inaudible],

00:47:54.790 --> 00:47:59.410 position:56%
by the name of Sin-leqi-unninni, who
may have been the principle editor

00:47:59.410 --> 00:48:02.870
of the text, who pulled together
all of this ancient material

00:48:02.870 --> 00:48:08.390
and crafted this one
canonical version perhaps.

00:48:08.390 --> 00:48:11.680
It's a very different story
than the one that we have

00:48:11.680 --> 00:48:14.760
in the Old Babylonian Period,
and, again, the very first line

00:48:14.760 --> 00:48:17.120
of the story reflects this.

00:48:17.120 --> 00:48:20.240
The standard Babylonian
version places emphasis

00:48:20.240 --> 00:48:24.220
on Gilgamesh's acquisition
of wisdom and self-knowledge

00:48:24.220 --> 00:48:29.070
through hard experience
and personal suffering.

00:48:29.070 --> 00:48:33.180
It's a somber reflection,
a less confident

00:48:33.180 --> 00:48:35.500
and more introspective story.

00:48:35.500 --> 00:48:39.780
And, again, you see this in the
first line-- he who saw the deep,

00:48:39.780 --> 00:48:41.490
the foundations, of the land--

00:48:41.490 --> 00:48:46.970
which contrast very nicely with
the earlier Old Babylonian title.

00:48:46.970 --> 00:48:49.690
Now, one of the things
we're interested

00:48:49.690 --> 00:48:53.300
in is how Sin-leqi-unninni,
if we can trust

00:48:53.300 --> 00:48:56.230
that ancient attribution,
changed the epic.

00:48:56.230 --> 00:49:00.380
So, in addition to shaping and
refocusing the theme and mood

00:49:00.380 --> 00:49:02.480
of the epic he, or another,

00:49:02.480 --> 00:49:07.790
made a number of concrete
changes that we can identify.

00:49:07.790 --> 00:49:11.900 position:56%
For instance, we have this beautiful
sweeping prologue at the beginning

00:49:11.900 --> 00:49:15.990
of the epic that portrays it as
the autobiography of Gilgamesh.

00:49:15.990 --> 00:49:18.370
This didn't exist in
earlier versions.

00:49:18.370 --> 00:49:21.920
The transformation of Enkidu,
who plays a very minor role

00:49:21.920 --> 00:49:25.560
in the early Sumerian
stories, and now he's elevated

00:49:25.560 --> 00:49:29.130
to Gilgamesh's counterpart,
and sort of his alter ego.

00:49:29.130 --> 00:49:33.850
And we have the addition of
the final tablet of the epic,

00:49:33.850 --> 00:49:37.590
this mysterious tablet 12,
which is really an appendix

00:49:37.590 --> 00:49:41.410
to the 11-tablet epic, and it's
a literal translation of one

00:49:41.410 --> 00:49:43.640
of these earlier Sumerian stories--

00:49:43.640 --> 00:49:45.230
Gilgamesh, Enkidu and
the netherworld.

00:49:45.230 --> 00:49:48.380
And he did this as a show
probably of scholarly erudition

00:49:48.380 --> 00:49:54.630
to underscore the mortality
theme of the epic.

00:49:54.630 --> 00:49:58.280
More generally, Sin-leqi-unninni's
conceptualization

00:49:58.280 --> 00:50:02.360
of the epic is reflected in the
very structure of the narrative.

00:50:02.360 --> 00:50:06.150
The travels of Gilgamesh come
to encapsulate the known world

00:50:06.150 --> 00:50:10.070
and are symbolic of the
universality of the epic.

00:50:10.070 --> 00:50:13.940 position:56%
That is the sort of all-encompassing
theme of the epic is reflected

00:50:13.940 --> 00:50:17.420
in the physical action of
the narrative with Urok,

00:50:17.420 --> 00:50:21.480
the city par excellence, serving
as the anchor and focal point.

00:50:21.480 --> 00:50:25.320
The first half of the epic,
tablets three through five,

00:50:25.320 --> 00:50:28.910
are really an adventure
story out west.

00:50:28.910 --> 00:50:33.160
Right? Their travels are all done
in the western part of Mesopotamia

00:50:33.160 --> 00:50:35.070
at the Near Eastern world.

00:50:35.070 --> 00:50:39.660
The second half is a search
for this antediluvian wisdom,

00:50:39.660 --> 00:50:43.550
the wisdom of Utnapishtim
in the mythical east.

00:50:43.550 --> 00:50:47.780
So, what I would like to devote
the remainder of this talk to,

00:50:47.780 --> 00:50:51.550
and conclude with, is the
discovery of Gilgamesh

00:50:51.550 --> 00:50:54.630 position:56%
after it was lost for two millennia.

00:50:54.630 --> 00:50:56.930
The event, as I'd mentioned
at the outset,

00:50:56.930 --> 00:51:01.470
is bookended by two Assyrians--
one ancient and one modern.

00:51:01.470 --> 00:51:03.850
And I've already mentioned,
we've heard mention already,

00:51:03.850 --> 00:51:08.010
of the great seventh-century
Assyrian King Ashurbanipal

00:51:08.010 --> 00:51:12.500
and his famous library at
the capital of Nineveh.

00:51:12.500 --> 00:51:18.980
Ashurbanipal, as I mentioned, was
known for his claims to literacy

00:51:18.980 --> 00:51:22.230
and his love of learning, and
you can see him boasting about it

00:51:22.230 --> 00:51:28.710
in this quote, and of
course his famous library.

00:51:28.710 --> 00:51:33.440
Now, the library, actually
you have here is a letter

00:51:33.440 --> 00:51:36.310
from Ashurbanipal asking his agents

00:51:36.310 --> 00:51:38.940
to collect materials
for the library.

00:51:38.940 --> 00:51:43.520 position:56%
The library actually began
modestly with texts involving omens.

00:51:43.520 --> 00:51:47.150
But eventually it grew to
at least 25,000 tablets.

00:51:47.150 --> 00:51:50.130
You can see he's went far and
wide to collect this material.

00:51:50.130 --> 00:51:55.320
It included literary compositions
and other records of all kinds,

00:51:55.320 --> 00:51:58.970
and included multiple copies
of the Epic of Gilgamesh.

00:51:58.970 --> 00:52:02.600
There are probably at least four
copies of the Epic of Gilgamesh

00:52:02.600 --> 00:52:07.320
in Ashurbanipal's library, and
that, in fact, is our main source

00:52:07.320 --> 00:52:10.170
for the epic comes
from this library.

00:52:10.170 --> 00:52:14.230
When Nineveh fell in 612
B.C. the royal palace,

00:52:14.230 --> 00:52:15.850 position:56%
and with it the library, were burnt.

00:52:15.850 --> 00:52:18.550
The library rooms collapsed
to the foundations

00:52:18.550 --> 00:52:22.160
of the building sending
25,000 tablets plunging

00:52:22.160 --> 00:52:25.950
into the palace foundations, and
they rested there undisturbed

00:52:25.950 --> 00:52:28.970
for two and a half thousand years.

00:52:28.970 --> 00:52:32.560
Now, fast forward to the
middle of the 19th century

00:52:32.560 --> 00:52:35.970
and we had the birth of ancient
Near Eastern archaeology.

00:52:35.970 --> 00:52:37.730
And a few things are
happening at this point.

00:52:37.730 --> 00:52:42.330 position:56%
We had the decipherment of cuneiform
by Rollinson and others, the French

00:52:42.330 --> 00:52:45.650
and British, often in
competition with one another,

00:52:45.650 --> 00:52:49.270
begin excavating Assyrian capitals
which were known for mentions

00:52:49.270 --> 00:52:51.970
in the bible and classical sources.

00:52:51.970 --> 00:52:55.990
But our interests lie in
the pioneering excavations

00:52:55.990 --> 00:52:59.710
of Nineveh [inaudible]
by Austen Henry Layard

00:52:59.710 --> 00:53:02.240
in the mid-19th century.

00:53:02.240 --> 00:53:07.450 position:56%
Now, he was primarily, at this point
these were really treasure seekers.

00:53:07.450 --> 00:53:09.540
Right? They're interested
in sculpture

00:53:09.540 --> 00:53:13.590
and these were shipped back to
the British Museum including,

00:53:13.590 --> 00:53:17.830
you can see here these, well,
we just heard about a lot

00:53:17.830 --> 00:53:20.000
about [inaudible] were shipped
back to the British Museum,

00:53:20.000 --> 00:53:24.990
and they also incidentally
found some tablets as well.

00:53:24.990 --> 00:53:28.830
Layard finds these were a
sensation in the United Kingdom.

00:53:28.830 --> 00:53:30.220
You could see them moving one

00:53:30.220 --> 00:53:32.320
of these [inaudible]
into the British Museum.

00:53:32.320 --> 00:53:37.220
There's a caricature of Layard
as writing on one of these bowls

00:53:37.220 --> 00:53:39.640
when he started his
political career.

00:53:39.640 --> 00:53:45.520
Some of these drawings were
actually made by Layard.

00:53:45.520 --> 00:53:46.820
He was an artist.

00:53:46.820 --> 00:53:49.950
You can see him here in the
