00:53:49.950 --> 00:53:53.920
These were very destructive
archaeologic treasure-hunting

00:53:53.920 --> 00:53:58.620
operations and very destructive
tunneling at Nineveh and Corsiva

00:53:58.620 --> 00:54:01.880
that they engaged in
to find these things.

00:54:01.880 --> 00:54:05.200
It was just how archaeology
was done at the time.

00:54:05.200 --> 00:54:08.360
But Layard actually
didn't work alone.

00:54:08.360 --> 00:54:10.270
He had an assistant who would go

00:54:10.270 --> 00:54:14.160
on to become his archaeological
successor, Hormuzd Rassam,

00:54:14.160 --> 00:54:17.580
who would play a critical role
in Near Eastern archaeology,

00:54:17.580 --> 00:54:20.730
and is really one of
its unsung heroes.

00:54:20.730 --> 00:54:24.950
Rassam was an ethnic Assyrian born
in Mosul, a Chaldean Christian.

00:54:24.950 --> 00:54:30.480
He was actually hired by
Layard as a paymaster in 1845.

00:54:30.480 --> 00:54:35.630
Layard was highly impressed with
Rassam, and he became something

00:54:35.630 --> 00:54:38.810
of a father figure to Rassam,
and the two remained friends

00:54:38.810 --> 00:54:42.190
for the next 50 years
until Layard's death.

00:54:42.190 --> 00:54:45.910
Eventually Rassam would
succeed Layard

00:54:45.910 --> 00:54:48.440
and the British Museum
entrusted Rassam

00:54:48.440 --> 00:54:51.360
with heading its excavations
in Iraq.

00:54:51.360 --> 00:54:55.750
Now, the field work was
conducted between 1852 and 54

00:54:55.750 --> 00:55:00.080
where Rassam really made a number
of astonishing discoveries.

00:55:00.080 --> 00:55:05.680 position:56%
In fact, it was Rassam, not Layard,
who excavated Ashurbanipal's library

00:55:05.680 --> 00:55:10.070
and palace, and discovered
all the tablets that would go

00:55:10.070 --> 00:55:11.580
on to make the nucleus

00:55:11.580 --> 00:55:14.630
of the British Museum's
fantastic tablet collection.

00:55:14.630 --> 00:55:18.850
And so it was Rassam who actually
discovered the Epic of Gilgamesh.

00:55:18.850 --> 00:55:23.800
Here you see two portraits of
Rassam that he sat for at the age

00:55:23.800 --> 00:55:28.700 position:56%
of 25 just before he became Director
of the British Museum excavations,

00:55:28.700 --> 00:55:33.650
and they really contrast
the Middle Eastern

00:55:33.650 --> 00:55:38.730 position:56%
and European dress symbolizes really
the ambivalence in Rassam's life.

00:55:38.730 --> 00:55:42.980
He belonged to both worlds in
name, but in reality, in the end,

00:55:42.980 --> 00:55:45.790
unfortunately, to neither.

00:55:45.790 --> 00:55:50.030
Now, Rassam's fortunes changed
for the worse once he returned

00:55:50.030 --> 00:55:54.890
to England where he found that
in the press his colleagues

00:55:54.890 --> 00:55:58.850
in the fields and at the British
Museum were either claiming his

00:55:58.850 --> 00:56:00.630
discoveries for themselves,

00:56:00.630 --> 00:56:02.860
or crediting his accomplishments
to others.

00:56:02.860 --> 00:56:05.820
And really this was an
issue of cultural prejudice

00:56:05.820 --> 00:56:07.980
in Victorian England
where many couldn't accept

00:56:07.980 --> 00:56:11.580
that a Middle Easterner had
made contributions of this kind.

00:56:11.580 --> 00:56:14.550
He was often described, for
instance, as a digger with Layard

00:56:14.550 --> 00:56:16.700
as the brains behind the operation.

00:56:16.700 --> 00:56:21.350
And this prejudice was to
plague him the rest of his life

00:56:21.350 --> 00:56:27.270 position:56%
after a disastrous stint in politics
Rassam resumed his archaeological

00:56:27.270 --> 00:56:30.100
career later in life, and
he made more important finds

00:56:30.100 --> 00:56:31.400
at Balwat in Sipar.

00:56:31.400 --> 00:56:35.550
However, he entered into a very
public dispute with this man

00:56:35.550 --> 00:56:39.200
in the lower right, Budge
of the British Museum,

00:56:39.200 --> 00:56:42.060
who actually accused him
of stealing artifacts.

00:56:42.060 --> 00:56:44.170
There was no evidence
for this, of course.

00:56:44.170 --> 00:56:49.610
Rassam sued Budge for slander
in a very famous lawsuit in 1893

00:56:49.610 --> 00:56:53.130
that was a sensation in the
U.K. covered by the press.

00:56:53.130 --> 00:56:56.890
He won the lawsuit, but was
awarded almost nothing in damages.

00:56:56.890 --> 00:57:00.260
He retired in Brighton
in debt, embittered,

00:57:00.260 --> 00:57:01.980
embarrassed and largely forgotten.

00:57:01.980 --> 00:57:06.230
But the field has, however, been
kinder to him in recent years.

00:57:06.230 --> 00:57:09.450
And there's been a real
effort to restore Rassam

00:57:09.450 --> 00:57:11.610
and his position in the field.

00:57:11.610 --> 00:57:15.890
Now, as for the Epic of Gilgamesh
itself after it was discovered,

00:57:15.890 --> 00:57:19.650
we have to fast forward 20
years from Rassam's discovery

00:57:19.650 --> 00:57:22.320
of Ashurbanipal's library.

00:57:22.320 --> 00:57:24.940
You have to remember,
or know, that Layard

00:57:24.940 --> 00:57:28.670
and Rassam couldn't read
the tablets that they found.

00:57:28.670 --> 00:57:32.340
Right? The decipherment of
Akkadian was in its infancy.

00:57:32.340 --> 00:57:39.340 position:56%
Enter a genius by the name of George
Smith from a working class family,

00:57:39.340 --> 00:57:44.550
limited formal education, but
fascinated with biblical history

00:57:44.550 --> 00:57:48.270
and the sensational Assyrian finds
that were being made at the time.

00:57:48.270 --> 00:57:51.630
He spent his lunch hours at
the British Museum training

00:57:51.630 --> 00:57:55.740
under Rollinson, who was one of the
principle decipherers of Akkadian

00:57:55.740 --> 00:57:57.690
and the father of Assyriology.

00:57:57.690 --> 00:58:01.000
George eventually got a
position at the British Museum,

00:58:01.000 --> 00:58:03.810
and began looking through
this vast tablet collection

00:58:03.810 --> 00:58:07.180
for a sensational tablet
that would make him a star,

00:58:07.180 --> 00:58:09.370
and make a big splash in the world.

00:58:09.370 --> 00:58:12.760
It took him five years to find
it sifting through these tablets,

00:58:12.760 --> 00:58:17.150
but in 1872 he found it, sorting
through the thousands of tablets

00:58:17.150 --> 00:58:19.430
in Ashurbanipal's library.

00:58:19.430 --> 00:58:23.980 position:56%
He found the best preserved
manuscript of tablet 11 of Gilgamesh

00:58:23.980 --> 00:58:27.630
which just so happens
recounts the flood.

00:58:27.630 --> 00:58:31.130
And this was an absolutely
sensational find

00:58:31.130 --> 00:58:34.400
as it not only corroborated
the biblical account

00:58:34.400 --> 00:58:36.470
of the flood, but it predated it.

00:58:36.470 --> 00:58:38.780
And, so, it showed
that a major episode

00:58:38.780 --> 00:58:42.780
of genesis had earlier
Mesopotamian origins.

00:58:42.780 --> 00:58:45.460
You can see here in
this quote from Budge--

00:58:45.460 --> 00:58:49.250
Rollinson's reaction upon
finding the tablet where he sort

00:58:49.250 --> 00:58:52.660
of took his clothes off in
a state of great excitement.

00:58:52.660 --> 00:58:55.750
Some people now actually think he
was suffering an epileptic fit, so,

00:58:55.750 --> 00:59:00.650
maybe is a different spin on this.

00:59:00.650 --> 00:59:08.730
To conclude, Smith presented his
findings at a very public meeting

00:59:08.730 --> 00:59:10.880
at the Society of Biblical
Archaeology

00:59:10.880 --> 00:59:14.100
where even Prime Minister
Gladstone was in attendance.

00:59:14.100 --> 00:59:15.800
It made international news.

00:59:15.800 --> 00:59:17.620
Actually you can see it here.

00:59:17.620 --> 00:59:22.470 position:56%
The Daily Telegraph was so impressed
with Smith's famous lecture

00:59:22.470 --> 00:59:25.130
on the flood that they
actually funded him to go back

00:59:25.130 --> 00:59:30.000
to Rassam's old trenches to find
missing pieces of the flood story.

00:59:30.000 --> 00:59:33.170
And that's really an incredible
thing to ask if you're familiar

00:59:33.170 --> 00:59:35.770
with these things because it's
like literally finding a needle

00:59:35.770 --> 00:59:39.140
in a haystack, finding
another bit of a tablet.

00:59:39.140 --> 00:59:42.830
But actually he succeeded in part.

00:59:42.830 --> 00:59:46.140
He found a portion of a
text that wasn't Gilgamesh,

00:59:46.140 --> 00:59:49.080
but a related text, but it
filled an important gap.

00:59:49.080 --> 00:59:53.630
This was a sensational
success for the Daily Telegraph

00:59:53.630 --> 00:59:55.620
that was funding this excavation.

00:59:55.620 --> 00:59:57.590
They couldn't ask for
a better outcome.

00:59:57.590 --> 01:00:02.040
He found it like within the second
or third day of returning to Iraq.

01:00:02.040 --> 01:00:03.990
However, he was a victim
of his own success,

01:00:03.990 --> 01:00:06.310
because once they had the
tablet they were looking

01:00:06.310 --> 01:00:10.750
for they cancelled the
expedition in the end.

01:00:10.750 --> 01:00:17.980
So, George Smith, in 1876
on a return trip to Iraq,

01:00:17.980 --> 01:00:20.650
he fell ill in Aleppo
and, unfortunately,

01:00:20.650 --> 01:00:24.060
died at a very young age of 36,

01:00:24.060 --> 01:00:26.110
which brings us to
the end of our story.

01:00:26.110 --> 01:00:29.610
And I would just point
out some further reading

01:00:29.610 --> 01:00:33.260
if you're interested, if you
read the Epic of Gilgamesh,

01:00:33.260 --> 01:00:36.060
and I hope you all do or have,

01:00:36.060 --> 01:00:41.100
you should read the exceptional
translation of Andrew George.

01:00:41.100 --> 01:00:43.630
I think it's the only
one you should read.

01:00:43.630 --> 01:00:49.100 position:56%
And then there are a number of other
very nice books on Assyrian legacy.

01:00:49.100 --> 01:00:54.300
There's another one by Mogens
Trolle Larsen called "The Conquest

01:00:54.300 --> 01:00:56.660
of Assyria" which is excellent,
but I think, unfortunately,

01:00:56.660 --> 01:00:59.670
out of print and very expensive.

01:00:59.670 --> 01:01:01.900
There's "Empires of the Plain"

01:01:01.900 --> 01:01:04.450
which recounts the
early pioneering efforts

01:01:04.450 --> 01:01:07.730 position:56%
of ancient Near Eastern archaeology.

01:01:07.730 --> 01:01:11.410
And "The Buried Book" is a book
about Gilgamesh, and it recounts

01:01:11.410 --> 01:01:16.530
in very nice detail the era
of Rollinson and Rassam,

01:01:16.530 --> 01:01:22.220
and the sort of fascinating
story that was their lives.

01:01:22.220 --> 01:01:24.510
Thank you very much.

01:01:24.510 --> 01:01:37.600
[ Clapping ]

01:01:37.600 --> 01:01:38.900
&gt;&gt; Mary Jane Deeb: Thank
you, Professor Woods,

01:01:38.900 --> 01:01:43.070
and for those who have read
Gilgamesh it's definitely

01:01:43.070 --> 01:01:44.370
an inspiration.

01:01:44.370 --> 01:01:45.670
Go back to it.

01:01:45.670 --> 01:01:47.480
Thank you.

01:01:47.480 --> 01:01:51.600
So, now we have Professor Simo
Parpola, Professor Emeritus

01:01:51.600 --> 01:01:54.530
of Assyriology at the
University of Helsinki.

01:01:54.530 --> 01:01:57.720
He specializes in the
new Assyrian Empire.

01:01:57.720 --> 01:02:02.060
His research interests encompass
all aspects of Assyrian language,

01:02:02.060 --> 01:02:05.880
culture and history,
especially Assyrian religion,

01:02:05.880 --> 01:02:08.550
royal ideology and sciences.

01:02:08.550 --> 01:02:11.850
The Melammu Project,
which he initiated,

01:02:11.850 --> 01:02:15.960
investigates the continuity,
transformation and diffusion

01:02:15.960 --> 01:02:20.420
of Assyrian and Babylonian culture
throughout the ancient world.

01:02:20.420 --> 01:02:23.670
In addition to his academic
activities Professor Parpola has

01:02:23.670 --> 01:02:25.890
also worked for the
benefit of oppressed

01:02:25.890 --> 01:02:31.050
and persecuted modern Assyrians,
and is co-founder and chairman

01:02:31.050 --> 01:02:34.450
of the Finland Assyria Association.

01:02:34.450 --> 01:02:36.510
Professor Parpola?

01:02:36.510 --> 01:02:44.280
[ Clapping ]

01:02:44.280 --> 01:02:46.570
&gt;&gt; Simo Parpola: Ladies
and gentlemen.

01:02:46.570 --> 01:02:48.400
Assyria is known from the bible

01:02:48.400 --> 01:02:53.860 position:56%
as a great military power oppressing
the Near East for centuries,

01:02:53.860 --> 01:02:55.600
only to be utterly destroyed

01:02:55.600 --> 01:02:59.470
and wiped off the face
of the Earth in the end.

01:02:59.470 --> 01:03:03.020
This notion of Assyria
is still very common,

01:03:03.020 --> 01:03:06.760
but it is misleading and wrong.

01:03:06.760 --> 01:03:12.120
The Assyrian Empire was much more
than just a cold military power.

01:03:12.120 --> 01:03:16.810
And when it fell it by no
means meant the end of Assyria

01:03:16.810 --> 01:03:21.510
and Assyrians, nor
the end of the empire.

01:03:21.510 --> 01:03:27.310
I have planned my talk so that
we will begin with having a look

01:03:27.310 --> 01:03:31.910
at what happened to Assyria and
Assyrians after the fall of Empire

01:03:31.910 --> 01:03:36.210
and then continue with a
look at the organization

01:03:36.210 --> 01:03:40.160
of the Empire at its heyday.

01:03:40.160 --> 01:03:44.860
We will see that the ideological
and administrative structures

01:03:44.860 --> 01:03:51.120
and methods needed to keep
everything going did not disappear,

01:03:51.120 --> 01:03:56.370
but remained in place even
after the fall of Assyria.

01:03:56.370 --> 01:03:59.110
They were as vital
to the functioning

01:03:59.110 --> 01:04:04.420
of all subsequent empires
as they had been to Assyria.

01:04:04.420 --> 01:04:11.210 position:56%
And thus came to have a profound and
lasting impact on the afterworld,

01:04:11.210 --> 01:04:14.930
both in the west and the east.

01:04:14.930 --> 01:04:22.790
The Assyrian Empire was the
United States of its time.

01:04:22.790 --> 01:04:29.100
It was a large multi-ethnic
scientific

01:04:29.100 --> 01:04:32.600
and technologically-advanced
country,

01:04:32.600 --> 01:04:36.870
and certainly the most
powerful country

01:04:36.870 --> 01:04:42.780
in the Eastern Mediterranean
and the Near East.

01:04:42.780 --> 01:04:51.240
Like the United States
it had been born,

01:04:51.240 --> 01:05:01.070
it grew from humble
beginnings by conquest.

01:05:01.070 --> 01:05:07.840
But through a very
efficient and effective policy

01:05:07.840 --> 01:05:15.960
of integration it was
able to unify the country

01:05:15.960 --> 01:05:25.500 position:56%
to a homogenous foe sharing a common
language, the imperial Aramaic,

01:05:25.500 --> 01:05:31.560
which was sort of the
equivalent of American English,

01:05:31.560 --> 01:05:37.810
which was spoken all over the
empire by people who had long

01:05:37.810 --> 01:05:45.920
since forgotten their ethnic
origins and shared values, religion

01:05:45.920 --> 01:05:47.370
and ideology of the empire.

01:05:47.370 --> 01:05:54.480
Even the ruling class,
which traced its origins

01:05:54.480 --> 01:06:00.690
in the Old Akkadian Empire
of the third millennial B.C.

01:06:00.690 --> 01:06:09.110
and spoke mainly Assyrian,
was totally bilingual.

01:06:09.110 --> 01:06:14.810
And probably some of
the elite who were

01:06:14.810 --> 01:06:22.960
of other ethnic origins also
shared the ideas of the empire.

01:06:22.960 --> 01:06:36.460
This is very important to keep in
mind when we look at what happened

01:06:36.460 --> 01:06:38.760
after the fall of Assyria.

01:06:45.040 --> 01:06:48.450
Well, you already have seen
pictures of the Assyrian Empire.

01:06:48.450 --> 01:06:52.600 position:56%
What we have here is just the extent

01:06:52.600 --> 01:06:59.800
of Assyria's provincial
administration.

01:06:59.800 --> 01:07:09.790
Actually Assyria was considered
a bit larger if you count

01:07:09.790 --> 01:07:18.380
in the vessel states, such as Lydia
and Phrygia in the Anatolia area

01:07:18.380 --> 01:07:27.200
and Urartu, now Armenia,
to the north of Assyria.

01:07:27.200 --> 01:07:35.610
In fact, Assyria's indirect
influence extended much farther

01:07:35.610 --> 01:07:45.010
than the [inaudible] area until
the [inaudible] Peninsula,

01:07:45.010 --> 01:07:51.580
that is to say now Spain,
because the Finnishians,

01:07:51.580 --> 01:07:58.270
who were experienced
vessels, acted for Assyrians

01:07:58.270 --> 01:08:03.880
in their commercial enterprises
and for [inaudible] silver mines

01:08:03.880 --> 01:08:08.410
in Spain, which were
important to the empire.

01:08:08.410 --> 01:08:20.720
Now, Assyria fell, as we have
heard, when Nineveh was destroyed

01:08:20.720 --> 01:08:29.780
in 612 B.C. as a result of a long
power struggle among the ruling

01:08:29.780 --> 01:08:36.500
elite which started with two sons
of Ashurbanipal fighting for power,

01:08:36.500 --> 01:08:45.780
and then ended up involving the
whole ruling elite including

01:08:45.780 --> 01:08:52.070
Assyrian governors in
Southern Babylonia and Media.

01:08:52.070 --> 01:09:06.020
In 612 Nineveh was [inaudible]
and razed to the ground,

01:09:06.020 --> 01:09:10.020
and the country was
divided into two parts--

01:09:10.020 --> 01:09:17.260
the Medes, who actually carried
out the destruction of Nineveh,

01:09:17.260 --> 01:09:28.530
carried away all the parts of the
governments that they were not able

01:09:28.530 --> 01:09:39.000
to escape from the city, and
deported much know-how not only

01:09:39.000 --> 01:09:41.070
from Ninevah, but also
from [inaudible]

01:09:41.070 --> 01:09:47.110
to their capital [inaudible]
in Western Iran.

01:09:47.110 --> 01:09:52.260
The Babylonians, under
the leadership

01:09:52.260 --> 01:09:58.790
of [inaudible] took the
western part of the empire,

01:09:58.790 --> 01:10:09.200
including Assyrian areas in
[inaudible] and Anatolia.

01:10:09.200 --> 01:10:16.640
So, it's important to remember
here that the actual seat

01:10:16.640 --> 01:10:21.250
of Assyrian government
remained on the Median side,

01:10:21.250 --> 01:10:26.070
and thus the Medes were able
to claim universal kinship.

01:10:26.070 --> 01:10:29.340
[inaudible] this appear
as heirs to the Assyrians,

01:10:29.340 --> 01:10:38.220 position:56%
whereas the Babylonians, who in fact
were just part of the old empire,

01:10:38.220 --> 01:10:46.000
could only claim the kinship of
Babylon because they were not

01:10:46.000 --> 01:10:51.040
on the scene when Assyria fell.

01:10:51.040 --> 01:10:57.310
Apart from the shift of the
power to [inaudible] and Babylon,

01:10:57.310 --> 01:11:04.380
and the liquidation of much
of the Assyrian abilities,

01:11:04.380 --> 01:11:10.610
nothing much happened elsewhere
otherwise in the empire.

01:11:10.610 --> 01:11:18.090
Life went on as it had been,
and both the Babylonians,

01:11:18.090 --> 01:11:20.090
and especially the Babylonians,

01:11:20.090 --> 01:11:27.410 position:56%
pursued the Assyrian policies before
the fall including, for instance,

01:11:27.410 --> 01:11:31.620
the deportations as we know
very well from the bible.

01:11:31.620 --> 01:11:42.790
So, here we have a map of the
new division of the empire.

01:11:42.790 --> 01:11:47.020
I must point out here that
the areas controlled by Media,

01:11:47.020 --> 01:11:51.310
which are much larger than
actually Assyria ever controlled,

01:11:51.310 --> 01:11:56.990
they are more loosely organized
than in the Assyrian Empire,

01:11:56.990 --> 01:12:04.870
and consisted of all sorts
of tributary arrangements

01:12:04.870 --> 01:12:10.370
between the Medes and
other Median tribes.

01:12:10.370 --> 01:12:15.670
Some have even contested
that a Median, its empire,

01:12:15.670 --> 01:12:22.790
actually ever existed, but I
believe there was an empire.

01:12:22.790 --> 01:12:31.570
And, in fact, it was very much
Assyrian, probably not only

01:12:31.570 --> 01:12:35.420
in organization, but also
in its habits as we'll learn

01:12:35.420 --> 01:12:39.890
from later historiographers.

01:12:41.930 --> 01:12:57.430
Well, some 70 years after Assyria's
fall both Media and Babylonia,

01:12:57.430 --> 01:13:05.220
near Babylonia, an empire came
under control of Cyrus the Great,

01:13:05.220 --> 01:13:07.230
who now became [inaudible]

01:13:07.230 --> 01:13:16.920
of all the countries
earlier ruled by Assyria.

01:13:16.920 --> 01:13:31.310 position:56%
It's incredible, but this
[inaudible] of time that had elapsed

01:13:31.310 --> 01:13:36.980
since the fall of Assyria
the Persians under Cyrus

01:13:36.980 --> 01:13:42.880
and his followers proved to be
even more faithful followers

01:13:42.880 --> 01:13:49.980
than Babylonians and Medes before
them of Assyrian practices.

01:13:49.980 --> 01:13:56.380
The former Assyrian area was
preserved under its former name,

01:13:56.380 --> 01:14:01.520
